{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "For Theorems 1 and 2 to hold, both m and r must grow.",
    "In practice, the trade-off between getting responses for more queries or getting more responses for the same queries depends on the distributions F ij.",
    "For example, if F ij is a point mass then r > 1 for q j is unnecessary.",
    "Conversely, if F ij is a complicated distribution on R p then more responses are necessary to properly estimate it and, hence, to properly capture the difference between average model responses.",
    "Lastly, we note that the data kernel perspective space could be used to extend the statistical Turing test framework presented in (Helm et al., 2023) by comparing the conditional distributions of populations of humans and populations of machines in low-dimensional Euclidean space."
  ],
